article.headline: Webber leads Kings to fifth straight victory
article.linkText: Turkoglu's late free throws lift Kings over Blazers
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Sacramento Kings know how to beat the Portland Trail Blazers despite being shorthanded.
Turkoglu

Hedo Turkoglu made a pair of free throws with 14.4 seconds remaining to lift the Sacramento Kings to a 95-94 win over the Portland Trail Blazers on Saturday night. The Kings beat Portland on Halloween without three starters and a reserve, and they were without two starters and two reserves Saturday. Already missing Mike Bibby, Sacramento played without forward Peja Stojakovic, who missed the game with plantar fasciitis in his right foot. The same injury kept him out of a Nov. 15 game at Seattle. Turkoglu, who scored 15 points, was fouled by Rasheed Wallace on a loose ball situation after Arvydas Sabonis tried to save an offensive rebound near the Kings bench. "We kept saying give yourself a chance to win in the final minute and that's what we did,'' Kings coach Rick Adelman said. "This was a great win for us. It's our fifth in seven nights and fourth in five nights.'' Chris Webber led Sacramento, which has won five in a row and eight of nine, with 24 points and 10 rebounds. Bobby Jackson added 22 points. "This was a big win for us on the road,'' Webber said. "We stuck with it and fought hard.'' The Blazers, who had a three-game winning streak snapped, had a chance at the end, but Sabonis' 15-foot baseline hook shot was well short, and Sabonis appeared to be fouled on the play. The non-call sent Portland coach Maurice Cheeks into a fit after the buzzer, screaming "That's terrible!'' at the officials. "It was a judgment call,'' Cheeks said. "Obviously the judgment didn't go our way. It looked like Sabes got fouled.'' Added guard Derek Anderson, who was also involved in the final play: "We came and played well. We should sleep easy tonight. The referees shouldn't sleep easy, but we should sleep easy.'' Wallace, who along with guard Damon Stoudamire was cited for misdemeanor marijuana possession early Friday morning in Washington state, led the Blazers with 30 points and nine rebounds. Stoudamire did not play for the second game in a row and the third time in the last four. Wallace received some boos during introductions, but had many more people cheering for him. The only noticeable display by fans regarding the incident was a sign in the end zone seats near the Kings' bench that read, "Sign my weed 'Sheed.'' "That's not a distraction for us, we're all professionals,'' Blazers forward Scottie Pippen said. "We know what we have to do on the basketball court. Whatever issues happen off the court, that individual has to deal with it. Our mind is set on basketball once we come into the locker room.'' Reserve Zach Randolph played a key role in the fourth quarter, scoring nine of his 13 points in crunch time and continuing to impress on both ends of the floor. Bonzi Wells added 12 points and eight rebounds. Sabonis finished with 10 points and six boards. "Randolph was great,'' Cheeks said. "It might have been a boneheaded move on my part to take him out of the game because he was scoring down the stretch.'' Wallace ignited a 14-2 run in the second quarter with nine of his 20 first-half points as the Blazers built their biggest lead of the half, 48-37. Wallace was 8-for-12 from the floor, including 3-for-5 on 3-pointers. But the Kings responded with an 11-3 run to close the half and pulled within 48-46 at the break. Game notes
Sacramento was again without center Scot Pollard, who missed his ninth straight game with a stress fracture in his lower back, and guard Mateen Cleaves, who has missed every game with a stress fracture in his left foot. ... Portland fell to 65-11 all-time versus the Kings at home. ... Sacramento president Geoff Petrie, vice president Wayne Cooper, head coach Rick Adelman and assistant coaches John Wetzel, Elston Turner and Terry Porter have either played or coached for the Blazers.
